"The sea is ours": Bolivia hopes court will open waterway to the Pacific
Sailors patrol naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings flags with sea blue flags.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are covered with the motto: "The sea is ours. We are right
and duty to return to it.”
In landlocked Bolivia, the people can still remember a coastline lost to Chile, in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century. They long to sail in the Pacific again.
These hopes may be stronger than in many decades while Bolivia awaits the judgment of the International Court of Justice due on October 1, after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has drive, peace of mind and is united, and of course expects a positive result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the verdict of the International Court of Justice, in hopes that the Hague Court will support Bolivia's claim, and that Chile - after decades of negotiations - will give Bolivia an independent exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic native president of Bolivia - who is struggling to be re-elected next year - has good reason to hope for a positive result.
"Now we will soon be returning to the Pacific," he promised in late August.
However, some analysts do not believe the court will allow Bolivia to access the sea - and that little would have changed even if they were allowed access.
The Netherlands-based UN court has no power to transfer Chilean territory to Bolivia, and has stipulated that they will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
That the court's verdict comes just six months after the last negotiations, indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
The last four years have far from promoted Bolivia's cause, they have done the opposite.
"The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morales, with his belligerent rhetoric, has killed what was left of Chile's goodwill, Zárate said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the issue after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
The former president, Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who is Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually swift.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open new relations with Chile" and a chance to "set a bar at 139 years of disagreement and rather benefit both," he said.
Calzadilla also rejected that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, used this maritime issue to win votes.
"Bolivia will never give up the right of access to the Pacific," he added.
"Judgment is an opportunity to see what we need to do to forget the past."
