North Korea says there is no talk of rushing down unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's Foreign Minister told the United Nations Saturday that if sanctions continue, the distrust of the United States will increase and that the country would in no way give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Government's Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures" to improve conditions in the past year, for example, they have stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear test site and promise not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we will not get anything equivalent back from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances it is not possible for us to unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri, a well-known North Korean, has made several complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to the abolition of nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his statement proved significant in not rejecting unilateral nuclear demolition, such as Pyong has done.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first summit ever between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim vowed to work for "downsizing nuclear power on the Korean peninsula" while Trump vowed guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has wanted a formal end to the 1950–53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted talks to ease tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'downgrading nuclear power first' and increases the pressure with sanctions to achieve its purpose of coercion, and they even opposed the 'declaration of ceasing peace'," Ri said.
"The belief that sanctions can break us is a false hope among those who are not interested in us.
But the problem is that when the sanctions continue, our mistrust only increases."
Ri did not mention anything about the plans for a new summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader, Moon Jae-in, over the past five months and added: "If the party in this call for the downgrading of nuclear weapons were South Korea, and not the United States, the downgrading on the Korean peninsula would not have stopped as it has now done"
Nonetheless, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was not possible to stop North Korean missiles towards the U.S. mainland, after evil President Trump called Kim a missile man on suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said a lot of work still needed to be done and that sanctions needed to remain in place until North Korea dismantled its nuclear weapon.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a time frame for this, saying, "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should pay Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The sanctions of the Security Council must still be maintained vigorously and without fail until we get the complete, final, verified dismantling of the nuclear weapons."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to throttle Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a new summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemned him for making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took "equivalent action."
He said Kim had told him that the "equivalent measures" he sought were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Courses in Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has helped all students get more sleep, in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture of studying in caffeine rush all night long. That is, one uses caffeine to stay awake all night to study.
One academic found that students at top universities often recklessly when it comes to the most basic - how to take care of yourself.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I being told this now, in adulthood?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleeping - something that surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, rolled out for the first time this year, explains to students what is important for how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after students got seriously poorer sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers, and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as how important it is with evening routines.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
'We know it won't change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know, the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes, added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride over daytime still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring that you get enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's secret weapon against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even avoiding gaining weight, since lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, having been a student with him the previous year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before starting at the prestigious institution.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, and also for when to wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of "blue light" coming from electronic monitors and LED lighting, and which can reset the internal clock overall, leading to problems with falling asleep.
