Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and WE RECOGNIZE ... the day when he who was to become the physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
As a scientific carrier ever since, the Geiger counter also became a carrier in pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with the seemingly unlikely lazy cowboy researchers Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it can be used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these earphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms that come from the radioactivity of the minerals."
Evans: "Yes, now it populates!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name, lives on.
