This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as meadow acquisitions and how it is best to maintain equal forest areas for bats and other associated species.
Flag mice populations in Scotland and across the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work affecting rest areas and loss of habitat/bubble areas.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, such as flying paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are still more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to find errors and obstacles in their flight routes.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, resting place inspections and sometimes save lives.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated flagella reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten flagella species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitats.
But there is a lot about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance within properties, since it is possible that the endless destruction of a single buplas can kill up to 400 female bats and young, and perhaps annihilate an entire local population.
Flag mice are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their resting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to come in and help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are doing."
