Update on Dinoflagellates: Concentration Reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, uneven conditions for growth are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and the counties around Collier - suggesting a reduction in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates extends beyond about 200 km on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas with dinoflagellates are found approximately 16 km off the coast at Hillsborough, but compared to the previous week there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have been observed in Pasco.
There have been reports of medium-sized concentration in Pinellas over the past week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium-sized concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee and low concentration in Collier.
Airway irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Airway irritation was not reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
